The paper proposes a deep learning approach for the inverse problem of electrical resistivity surveys (ERS). The approach uses convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and is based on the prevalent U-Net architecture. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) and Graphics (cs.GR) sub-categories, as these are the most relevant areas for image processing and pattern recognition. Additionally, the paper involves the use of deep learning techniques, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of ill-posedness, which could make it relevant to the Signal Processing (cs.SI) sub-category.
